 interpretations of freedom that lead the subjects of these interpretations to no longer act and think freely. They are often unwillingly led into unfreedom. It is thus possible that even “freedom” enslaves. Modern philosophical rationalism, whose conceptual genealogy the books traces and unfolds, assigns a name to this peculiar form of domination by means of freedom: indifference. Indifference is a name for the assumption that freedom is something that human beings have: a given, a natural possession. When we think freedom is natural or a possession we lose freedom. Modern philosophy, Ruda shows, takes its shape through repeated attacks on freedom as indifference; it is the owl that begins its flight, so that the days of unfreedom will turn to dusk.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aApathyxPhilosophy. 0aLibertyxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh  aAngela Davis.  aBadiou.  aDescartes.  aEmancipation Revolution.  aHegel.  aKant.  aLenin.  aMarx.  aSilvia Federici.  aZizek.1 aBadiou, Alain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYeung, Heather H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishz978311131922308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023z9783111318646oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531505349?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531505349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531505349